# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fasthttp-go
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] A third-party source-to-source compiler, GopherJS, transpiles Go to JavaScript for front-end web development.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Go was designed at Google in 2007 to improve programming productivity in an era of multicore, networked machines and large codebases.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Its designers were primarily motivated by their shared dislike of C++.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Go was publicly announced in November 2009, and version 1.0 was released in March 2012.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Go is widely used in production at Google and in many other organizations and open-source projects.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] In retrospect the Go authors judged Go to be successful due to the overall engineering work around the language, including the runtime support for the language's concurrency feature.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The gopher mascot was introduced in 2009 for the open source launch of the language.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Renée French, who had designed the rabbit mascot for Plan 9, adapted the gopher from an earlier WFMU T-shirt design.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] In November 2016, the Go and Go Mono fonts were released by type designers Charles Bigelow and Kris Holmes specifically for use by the Go project.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Go is a humanist sans-serif resembling Lucida Grande, and Go Mono is monospaced.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Both fonts adhere to the WGL4 character set and were designed to be legible with a large x-height and distinct letterforms.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Both Go and Go Mono adhere to the DIN 1450 standard by having a slashed zero, lowercase `i` with a tail, and an uppercase `I` with serifs.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] In April 2018, the original logo was redesigned by brand designer Adam Smith.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The new logo is a modern, stylized GO slanting right with trailing streamlines.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The lack of support for generic programming in initial versions of Go drew considerable criticism.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The designers expressed an openness to generic programming and noted that built-in functions *were* in fact type-generic, but are treated as special cases; Pike called this a weakness that might be changed at some point.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The Google team built at least one compiler for an experimental Go dialect with generics, but did not release it.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] In August 2018, the Go principal contributors published draft designs for generic programming and error handling and asked users to submit feedback.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] However, the error handling proposal was eventually abandoned.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] In June 2020, a new draft design document was published that would add the necessary syntax to Go for declaring generic functions and types.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] A code translation tool, *go2go*, was provided to allow users to try the new syntax, along with a generics-enabled version of the online Go Playground.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Generics were finally added to Go in version 1.18 on March 15, 2022.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Go 1 guarantees compatibility for the language specification and major parts of the standard library.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] All versions up through the current Go 1.26 release have maintained this promise.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Go uses a `go1.[major].[patch]` versioning format, such as `go1.26.0` and each major Go release is supported until there are two newer major releases.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Unlike most software, Go calls the second number in a version the major, i.e., in `go1.26.0` the `26` is the major version.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] This is because Go plans to never reach 2.0, prioritizing backwards compatibility over potential breaking changes.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Go is influenced by C (especially the Plan 9 dialect), but with an emphasis on greater simplicity and safety.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Go's syntax includes changes from C aimed at keeping code concise and readable.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] A combined declaration/initialization operator was introduced that allows the programmer to write `i := 3` or `s := "Hello, world!"`, without specifying the types of variables used.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] This contrasts with C's `int i = 3;` and `char *s = "Hello, world!";` (though since C23 type inference has been supported using `auto`, like C++).
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Go also removes the requirement to use parentheses in `if` statement conditions.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Semicolons still terminate statements; but are implicit when the end of a line occurs.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Methods may return multiple values, and returning a `result, err` pair is the conventional way a method indicates an error to its caller in Go.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Go adds literal syntaxes for initializing struct parameters by name and for initializing maps and slices.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] As an alternative to C's three-statement `for` loop, Go's `range` expressions allow concise iteration over arrays, slices, strings, maps, and channels.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Go has a number of built-in types, including numeric ones (`byte`, `int64`, `float32`, etc.), Booleans, and byte strings (`string`).
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Strings are immutable; built-in operators and keywords (rather than functions) provide concatenation, comparison, and UTF-8 encoding/decoding.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Record types can be defined with the `struct` keyword.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Note that `byte` is an alias for `uint8` and `rune` is an alias for `int32`.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] For each type `T` and each non-negative integer constant `n`, there is an array type denoted `[n]T`; arrays of differing lengths are thus of different types.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Dynamic arrays are available as "slices", denoted `[]T` for some type `T` (compare to other languages like C/C++ and Java, where instead the arrays are denoted `T[]`) These have a length and a *capacity* specifying when new memory needs to be allocated to expand the array.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Several slices may share their underlying memory.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] For a pair of types `K`, `V`, the type `map[K]V` is the type mapping type-`K` keys to type-`V` values, which can be thought of as equivalent to `Map<K, V>` in other languages.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The Go Programming Language specification does not give any performance guarantees or implementation requirements for map types, though it is usually implemented as a hash table (equivalent to `HashMap<K, V>` in other languages).
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Hash tables are built into the language, with special syntax and built-in functions.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] `chan T` is a *channel* that allows sending values of type `T` between concurrent Go processes.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Aside from its support for interfaces, Go's type system is nominal: the `type` keyword can be used to define a new *named type*, which is distinct from other named types that have the same layout (in the case of a `struct`, the same members in the same order).
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Some conversions between types (e.g., between the various integer types) are pre-defined and adding a new type may define additional conversions, but conversions between named types must always be invoked explicitly.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] With this type definition, `ipv4addr(x)` interprets the `uint32` value `x` as an IP address.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Simply assigning `x` to a variable of type `ipv4addr` is a type error.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Any named type has a method set associated with it.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Due to nominal typing, this method definition adds a method to `ipv4addr`, but not on `uint32`.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] While methods have special definition and call syntax, there is no distinct method type.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Go provides two features that replace class inheritance.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The first is *embedding*, which can be viewed as an automated form of composition.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The second are its *interfaces*, which provides runtime polymorphism.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Interfaces are a class of types and provide a limited form of structural typing in the otherwise nominal type system of Go.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] An object which is of an interface type is also of another type, much like C++ objects being simultaneously of a base and derived class.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The design of Go interfaces was inspired by protocols from the Smalltalk programming language.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Multiple sources use the term duck typing when describing Go interfaces.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Although the term duck typing is not precisely defined and therefore not wrong, it usually implies that type conformance is not statically checked.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Because conformance to a Go interface is checked statically by the Go compiler (except when performing a type assertion), the Go authors prefer the term *structural typing*.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The definition of an interface type lists required methods by name and type.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Any object of type T for which functions exist matching all the required methods of interface type I is an object of type I as well.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The definition of type T need not (and cannot) identify type I.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] then both a `Square` and a `Circle` are implicitly a `Shape` and can be assigned to a `Shape`-typed variable.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] In formal language, Go's interface system provides structural rather than nominal typing.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Interfaces can embed other interfaces with the effect of creating a combined interface that is satisfied by exactly the types that implement the embedded interface and any methods that the newly defined interface adds.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The Go standard library uses interfaces to provide genericity in several places, including the input/output system that is based on the concepts of `Reader` and `Writer`.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Besides calling methods via interfaces, Go allows converting interface values to other types with a run-time type check.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The *empty interface* `interface{}` is an important base case because it can refer to an item of *any* concrete type.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] It is similar to the `Object` class in Java or C# or `void*` in C or `Any` in C++ and Rust and is satisfied by any type, including built-in types like `int`.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Code using the empty interface cannot simply call methods (or built-in operators) on the referred-to object, but it can store the `interface{}` value, try to convert it to a more useful type via a type assertion or type switch, or inspect it with Go's `reflect` package.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Because `interface{}` can refer to any value, it is a limited way to escape the restrictions of static typing, like `void*` in C but with additional run-time type checks.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The `interface{}` type can be used to model structured data of any arbitrary schema in Go, such as JSON or YAML data, by representing it as a `map[string]interface{}` (map of string to empty interface).
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] This recursively describes data in the form of a dictionary with string keys and values of any type.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Interface values are implemented using pointer to data and a second pointer to run-time type information.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Like some other types implemented using pointers in Go, interface values are `nil` if uninitialized.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Since version 1.18, Go supports generic code using parameterized types.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Functions and types now have the ability to be generic using type parameters.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] These type parameters are specified within square brackets, right after the function or type name.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The compiler transforms the generic function or type into non-generic by substituting *type arguments* for the type parameters provided, either explicitly by the user or type inference by the compiler.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] This transformation process is referred to as type instantiation.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Interfaces now can define a set of types (known as type set) using `|` (Union) operator, as well as a set of methods.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] These changes were made to support type constraints in generics code.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] For a generic function or type, a constraint can be thought of as the type of the type argument: a meta-type.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] This new `~T` syntax will be the first use of `~` as a token in Go.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] `~T` means the set of all types whose underlying type is `T`.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Go uses the `iota` identifier to create enumerated constants.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] In Go's package system, each package has a path (e.g., `"compress/bzip2"` or `"golang.org/x/net/html"`) and a name (e.g., `bzip2` or `html`).
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] By default other packages' definitions must *always* be prefixed with the other package's name.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] However the name used can be changed from the package name, and if imported as `_`, then no package prefix is required.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Only the *capitalized* names from other packages are accessible: `io.Reader` is public but `bzip2.reader` is not.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The Go language has built-in facilities, as well as library support, for writing concurrent programs.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The runtime is asynchronous: program execution that performs, for example, a network read will be suspended until data is available to process, allowing other parts of the program to perform other work.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] This is built into the runtime and does not require any changes in program code.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The go runtime also automatically schedules concurrent operations (goroutines) across multiple CPUs; this can achieve parallelism for a properly written program.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The primary concurrency construct is the *goroutine*, a type of green thread.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] A function call prefixed with the `go` keyword starts a function in a new goroutine.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] While a standard library package featuring most of the classical concurrency control structures (mutex locks, etc.) is available, idiomatic concurrent programs instead prefer *channels*, which send messages between goroutines.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Optional buffers store messages in FIFO order and allow sending goroutines to proceed before their messages are received.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Channels are typed, so that a channel of type `chan T` can only be used to transfer messages of type `T`.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Special syntax is used to operate on them; `<-ch` is an expression that causes the executing goroutine to block until a value comes in over the channel `ch`, while `ch <- x` sends the value `x` (possibly blocking until another goroutine receives the value).
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The built-in `switch`-like `select` statement can be used to implement non-blocking communication on multiple channels; see below for an example.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Go has a memory model describing how goroutines must use channels or other operations to safely share data.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The existence of channels does not by itself set Go apart from actor model-style concurrent languages like Erlang, where messages are addressed directly to actors (corresponding to goroutines).
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] In the actor model, channels are themselves actors, therefore addressing a channel just means to address an actor.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The actor style can be simulated in Go by maintaining a one-to-one correspondence between goroutines and channels, but the language allows multiple goroutines to share a channel or a single goroutine to send and receive on multiple channels.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] From these tools one can build concurrent constructs like worker pools, pipelines (in which, say, a file is decompressed and parsed as it downloads), background calls with timeout, "fan-out" parallel calls to a set of services, and others.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Channels have also found uses further from the usual notion of interprocess communication, like serving as a concurrency-safe list of recycled buffers, implementing coroutines (which helped inspire the name *goroutine*), and implementing iterators.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Concurrency-related structural conventions of Go (channels and alternative channel inputs) are derived from Tony Hoare's communicating sequential processes model.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Unlike previous concurrent programming languages such as Occam or Limbo (a language on which Go co-designer Rob Pike worked), Go does not provide any built-in notion of safe or verifiable concurrency.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] While the communicating-processes model is favored in Go, it is not the only one: all goroutines in a program share a single address space.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] This means that mutable objects and pointers can be shared between goroutines; see § Lack of data race safety, below.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Although Go's concurrency features are not aimed primarily at parallel processing, they can be used to program shared-memory multi-processor machines.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Various studies have been done into the effectiveness of this approach.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] One of these studies compared the size (in lines of code) and speed of programs written by a seasoned programmer not familiar with the language and corrections to these programs by a Go expert (from Google's development team), doing the same for Chapel, Cilk and Intel TBB.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The study found that the non-expert tended to write divide-and-conquer algorithms with one `go` statement per recursion, while the expert wrote distribute-work-synchronize programs using one goroutine per processor core.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The expert's programs were usually faster, but also longer.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Go's approach to concurrency can be summarized as "don't communicate by sharing memory; share memory by communicating".
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] There are no restrictions on how goroutines access shared data, making data races possible.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Specifically, unless a program explicitly synchronizes via channels or other means, writes from one goroutine might be partly, entirely, or not at all visible to another, often with no guarantees about ordering of writes.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Furthermore, Go's *internal data structures* like interface values, slice headers, hash tables, and string headers are not immune to data races, so type and memory safety can be violated in multithreaded programs that modify shared instances of those types without synchronization.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Instead of language support, safe concurrent programming thus relies on conventions; for example, Chisnall recommends an idiom called "aliases xor mutable", meaning that passing a mutable value (or pointer) over a channel signals a transfer of ownership over the value to its receiver.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The gc toolchain has an optional data race detector that can check for unsynchronized access to shared memory during runtime since version 1.1, additionally a best-effort race detector is also included by default since version 1.6 of the gc runtime for access to the `map` data type.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The linker in the gc toolchain creates statically linked binaries by default; therefore all Go binaries include the Go runtime.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Go deliberately omits certain features common in other languages, including (implementation) inheritance, assertions, pointer arithmetic, implicit type conversions, untagged unions, and tagged unions.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The designers added only those facilities that all three agreed on.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Of the omitted language features, the designers explicitly argue against assertions and pointer arithmetic, while defending the choice to omit type inheritance as giving a more useful language, encouraging instead the use of interfaces to achieve dynamic dispatch and composition to reuse code.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Exception handling was initially omitted in Go due to lack of a "design that gives value proportionate to the complexity".
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] An exception-like `panic`/`recover` mechanism that avoids the usual `try-catch` control structure was proposed and released in the March 30, 2010 snapshot.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The Go authors advise using it for unrecoverable errors such as those that should halt an entire program or server request, or as a shortcut to propagate errors up the stack within a package.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Across package boundaries, Go includes a canonical error type, and multi-value returns using this type are the standard idiom.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] It also includes profiling and debugging support, fuzzing capabilities to detect bugs, runtime instrumentation (for example, to track garbage collection pauses), and a data race detector.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Another tool maintained by the Go team but is not included in Go distributions is `gopls`, a language server that provides IDE features such as intelligent code completion to Language Server Protocol compatible editors.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] An ecosystem of third-party tools adds to the standard distribution, such as `gocode`, which enables code autocompletion in many text editors, `goimports`, which automatically adds/removes package imports as needed, and `errcheck`, which detects code that might unintentionally ignore errors.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] where "fmt" is the package for *formatted I/O*, similar to C's <stdio.h> or C++ <print>.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The following simple program demonstrates Go's concurrency features to implement an asynchronous program.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] It launches two lightweight threads ("goroutines"): one waits for the user to type some text, while the other implements a timeout.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The select statement waits for either of these goroutines to send a message to the main routine, and acts on the first message to arrive (example adapted from David Chisnall's book).
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The testing package provides support for automated testing of go packages.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] It is possible to run tests in parallel.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The net/http package provides support for creating web applications.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] This example would show "Hello world!" when localhost:8080 is visited.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Go has found widespread adoption in various domains due to its robust standard library and ease of use.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The interface system, and the deliberate omission of inheritance, were praised by Michele Simionato, who likened these characteristics to those of Standard ML, calling it "a shame that no popular language has followed [this] particular route".
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] By June 2015, its ranking had dropped to below 50th in the index, placing it lower than COBOL and Fortran.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] But as of January 2017, its ranking had surged to 13th, indicating significant growth in popularity and adoption.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] Go was again awarded TIOBE Programming Language of the Year in 2016.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] The evaluation got a rebuttal from the Go development team.
[src:fasthttp-go/go-programming-language] On November 10, 2009, the day of the general release of the language, Francis McCabe, developer of the Go! programming language (note the exclamation point), requested a name change of Google's language to prevent confusion with his language, which he had spent 10 years developing.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] include the representation data in the body.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following is a request with no body.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:fasthttp-go/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] A **network socket** is a software structure within a network node of a computer network that serves as an endpoint for sending and receiving data across the network.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] The structure and properties of a socket are defined by an application programming interface (API) for the networking architecture.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Sockets are created only during the lifetime of a process of an application running in the node.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Because of the standardization of the TCP/IP protocols in the development of the Internet, the term *network socket* is most commonly used in the context of the Internet protocol suite, and is therefore often also referred to as **Internet socket**.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] In this context, a socket is externally identified to other hosts by its **socket address**, which is the triad of transport protocol, IP address, and port number.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] The term *socket* is also used for the software endpoint of node-internal inter-process communication (IPC), which often uses the same API as a network socket.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] The use of the term *socket* in software is analogous to the function of an electrical female connector, a device in hardware for communication between nodes interconnected with an electrical cable.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Similarly, the term *port* refers to external physical endpoints at a node or device.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] The application programming interface (API) for the network protocol stack creates a handle for each socket created by an application, commonly referred to as a *socket descriptor*.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] In Unix-like operating systems, this descriptor is a type of file descriptor.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] It is stored by the application process for use with every read and write operation on the communication channel.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] At the time of creation with the API, a network socket is bound to the combination of a type of network protocol to be used for transmissions, a network address of the host, and a port number.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Ports are numbered resources that represent another type of software structure of the node.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] They are used as service types, and, once created by a process, serve as an externally (from the network) addressable location component, so that other hosts may establish connections.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Network sockets may be dedicated for persistent connections for communication between two nodes, or they may participate in connectionless and multicast communications.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] In practice, due to the proliferation of the TCP/IP protocols in use on the Internet, the term *network socket* usually refers to use with the Internet Protocol (IP).
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] It is therefore often also called **Internet socket**.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] An application can communicate with a remote process by exchanging data with TCP/IP by knowing the combination of protocol type, IP address, and port number.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] This combination is often known as a *socket address*.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] It is the network-facing access handle to the network socket.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] The remote process establishes a network socket in its own instance of the protocol stack and uses the networking API to connect to the application, presenting its own socket address for use by the application.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] A protocol stack, usually provided by the operating system (rather than as a separate library, for instance), is a set of services that allows processes to communicate over a network using the protocols that the stack implements.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] The operating system forwards the payload of incoming IP packets to the corresponding application by extracting the socket address information from the IP and transport protocol headers and stripping the headers from the application data.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] The application programming interface (API) that programs use to communicate with the protocol stack, using network sockets, is called a **socket API**.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Development of application programs that utilize this API is called *socket programming* or *network programming*.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Internet socket APIs are usually based on the Berkeley sockets standard.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] In the Berkeley sockets standard, sockets are a form of file descriptor, due to the Unix philosophy that "everything is a file", and the analogies between sockets and files.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Both have functions to read, write, open, and close.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] In practice, the differences strain the analogy, and different interfaces (send and receive) are used on a socket.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] In inter-process communication, each end generally has its own socket.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] In the standard Internet protocols TCP and UDP, a socket address is the combination of an IP address and a port number, much like one end of a telephone connection is the combination of a phone number and a particular extension.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Sockets need not have a source address, for example, for only sending data, but if a program *binds* a socket to a source address, the socket can be used to receive data sent to that address.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Based on this address, Internet sockets deliver incoming data packets to the appropriate application process.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] The distinctions between a socket (internal representation), socket descriptor (abstract identifier), and socket address (public address) are subtle, and these are not always distinguished in everyday usage.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Further, specific definitions of a *socket* differ between authors.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] In IETF Request for Comments, Internet Standards, in many textbooks, as well as in this article, the term *socket* refers to an entity that is uniquely identified by the socket number.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] In other textbooks, the term *socket* refers to a local socket address, i.e., a "combination of an IP address and a port number".
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] In the original definition of *socket* given in RFC 147, as it was related to the ARPA network in 1971, *"the socket is specified as a 32-bit number with even sockets identifying receiving sockets and odd sockets identifying sending sockets."* Today, however, socket communications are bidirectional.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Within the operating system and the application that created a socket, a socket is referred to by a unique integer value called a *socket descriptor*.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] On Unix-like operating systems and Microsoft Windows, the command-line tools netstat or ss are used to list established sockets and related information.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] This example in Java, modeled according to the Berkeley socket interface, sends the string "Hello, world!" via TCP to port `80` of the host with address `203.0.113.0`.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Each packet sent or received on a datagram socket is individually addressed and routed.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Order and reliability are not guaranteed with datagram sockets, so multiple packets sent from one machine or process to another may arrive in any order or might not arrive at all.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] In order to receive broadcast packets, a datagram socket should not be bound to a specific address, though in some implementations, broadcast packets may also be received when a datagram socket is bound to a specific address.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] and unique flow of error-free data without record boundaries, with well-defined mechanisms for creating and destroying connections and reporting errors.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] On the Internet, stream sockets are typically implemented using TCP so that applications can run across any network using TCP/IP protocol.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Allow direct sending and receiving of IP packets without any protocol-specific transport layer formatting.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] according to the chosen transport layer protocol (e.g.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] When reading from a raw socket, the headers are usually included.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] When transmitting packets from a raw socket, the automatic addition of a header is optional.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] (APIs), for example, those based on Berkeley sockets, support raw sockets.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] interface, but three years later, Microsoft limited Winsock's raw socket support because of security concerns.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Other socket types are implemented over other transport protocols, such as Systems Network Architecture and Unix domain sockets for internal inter-process communication.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Computer processes that provide application services are referred to as servers, and create sockets on startup that are in the *listening state*.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] These sockets are waiting for initiatives from client programs.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] A TCP server may serve several clients concurrently by creating a unique dedicated socket for each client connection in a new child process or processing thread for each client.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] These are in the *established state* when a socket-to-socket virtual connection or virtual circuit (VC), also known as a TCP session, is established with the remote socket, providing a duplex byte stream.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] A server may create several concurrently established TCP sockets with the same local port number and local IP address, each mapped to its own server-child process, serving its own client process.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] They are treated as different sockets by the operating system since the remote socket address (the client IP address or port number) is different; i.e., since they have different socket pair tuples.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] UDP sockets do not have an *established state*, because the protocol is connectionless.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] A UDP server process handles incoming datagrams from all remote clients sequentially through the same socket.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] UDP sockets are not identified by the remote address, but only by the local address, although each message has an associated remote address that can be retrieved from each datagram with the networking application programming interface (API).
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Local and remote sockets communicating over TCP are called **socket pairs**.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Each socket pair is described by a unique 4-tuple consisting of source and destination IP addresses and port numbers, i.e. of local and remote socket addresses.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] As discussed above, in the TCP case, a socket pair is associated on each end of the connection with a unique 4-tuple.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] The term *socket* dates to the publication of RFC 147 in 1971, when it was used in the ARPANET.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Most modern implementations of sockets are based on Berkeley sockets (1983), and other stacks such as Winsock (1991).
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] The Berkeley sockets API in the Berkeley Software Distribution (BSD) originated with the 4.2BSD Unix operating system as an API.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Only in 1989, however, could UC Berkeley release versions of its operating system and networking library free from the licensing constraints of AT&T's copyright-protected Unix.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] 1987, AT&T introduced the STREAMS-based Transport Layer Interface (TLI) in UNIX System V Release 3 (SVR3). and continued into Release 4 (SVR4).
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Other early implementations were written for TOPS-20, MVS, VM, IBM-DOS (PCIP).
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] The socket is primarily a concept used in the transport layer of the Internet protocol suite or session layer of the OSI model.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Networking equipment such as routers, which operate at the internet layer, and switches, which operate at the link layer, do not require implementations of the transport layer.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] However, stateful network firewalls, network address translators, and proxy servers keep track of active socket pairs.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] In multilayer switches and quality of service (QoS) support in routers, packet flows may be identified by extracting information about the socket pairs.
[src:fasthttp-go/network-socket] Raw sockets are typically available in network equipment and are used for routing protocols such as IGRP and OSPF, and for Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP).
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] In computer science, an algorithm is called **non-blocking** if failure or suspension of any thread cannot cause failure or suspension of another thread; for some operations, these algorithms provide a useful alternative to traditional blocking implementations.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] A non-blocking algorithm is **lock-free** if there is guaranteed system-wide progress, and **wait-free** if there is also guaranteed per-thread progress.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] "Non-blocking" was used as a synonym for "lock-free" in the literature until the introduction of obstruction-freedom in 2003.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] The word "non-blocking" was traditionally used to describe telecommunications networks that could route a connection through a set of relays "without having to re-arrange existing calls" (see Clos network).
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Also, if the telephone exchange "is not defective, it can always make the connection" (see nonblocking minimal spanning switch).
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] The traditional approach to multi-threaded programming is to use locks to synchronize access to shared resources.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Synchronization primitives such as mutexes, semaphores, and critical sections are all mechanisms by which a programmer can ensure that certain sections of code do not execute concurrently, if doing so could corrupt shared memory structures.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] If one thread attempts to acquire a lock that is already held by another thread, the thread will block until the lock is free.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Blocking a thread can be undesirable for many reasons.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] An obvious reason is that while the thread is blocked, it cannot accomplish anything: if the blocked thread had been performing a high-priority or real-time task, it would be highly undesirable to halt its progress.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] For example, certain interactions between locks can lead to error conditions such as deadlock, livelock, and priority inversion.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Using locks also involves a trade-off between coarse-grained locking, which can significantly reduce opportunities for parallelism, and fine-grained locking, which requires more careful design, increases locking overhead and is more prone to bugs.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Unlike blocking algorithms, non-blocking algorithms do not suffer from these downsides, and in addition are safe for use in interrupt handlers: even though the preempted thread cannot be resumed, progress is still possible without it.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] In contrast, global data structures protected by mutual exclusion cannot safely be accessed in an interrupt handler, as the preempted thread may be the one holding the lock.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] While this can be rectified by masking interrupt requests during the critical section, this requires the code in the critical section to have bounded (and preferably short) running time, or excessive interrupt latency may be observed.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] A lock-free data structure can be used to improve performance.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] A lock-free data structure increases the amount of time spent in parallel execution rather than serial execution, improving performance on a multi-core processor, because access to the shared data structure does not need to be serialized to stay coherent.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] With few exceptions, non-blocking algorithms use atomic read-modify-write primitives that the hardware must provide, the most notable of which is compare and swap (CAS).
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Critical sections are almost always implemented using standard interfaces over these primitives (in the general case, critical sections will be blocking, even when implemented with these primitives).
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] In the 1990s all non-blocking algorithms had to be written "natively" with the underlying primitives to achieve acceptable performance.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] However, the emerging field of software transactional memory promises standard abstractions for writing efficient non-blocking code.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Much research has also been done in providing basic data structures such as stacks, queues, sets, and hash tables.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] These allow programs to easily exchange data between threads asynchronously.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Additionally, some non-blocking data structures are weak enough to be implemented without special atomic primitives.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Several libraries internally use lock-free techniques, but it is difficult to write lock-free code that is correct.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Non-blocking algorithms generally involve a series of read, read-modify-write, and write instructions in a carefully designed order.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Optimizing compilers can aggressively re-arrange operations.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Even when they don't, many modern CPUs often re-arrange such operations (they have a "weak consistency model"), unless a memory barrier is used to tell the CPU not to reorder.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] C++11 programmers can use `std::atomic` in `<atomic>`, and C11 programmers can use `<stdatomic.h>`, both of which supply types and functions that tell the compiler not to re-arrange such instructions, and to insert the appropriate memory barriers.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Wait-freedom is the strongest non-blocking guarantee of progress, combining guaranteed system-wide throughput with starvation-freedom.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] An algorithm is wait-free if every operation has a bound on the number of steps the algorithm will take before the operation completes.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] This property is critical for real-time systems and is always nice to have as long as the performance cost is not too high.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] It was shown in the 1980s that all algorithms can be implemented wait-free, and many transformations from serial code, called *universal constructions*, have been demonstrated.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] However, the resulting performance does not in general match even naïve blocking designs.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Several papers have since improved the performance of universal constructions, but still, their performance is far below blocking designs.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Several papers have investigated the difficulty of creating wait-free algorithms.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] For example, it has been shown that the widely available atomic *conditional* primitives, CAS and LL/SC, cannot provide starvation-free implementations of many common data structures without memory costs growing linearly in the number of threads.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] However, these lower bounds do not present a real barrier in practice, as spending a cache line or exclusive reservation granule (up to 2 KB on ARM) of store per thread in the shared memory is not considered too costly for practical systems.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Typically, the amount of store logically required is a word, but physically CAS operations on the same cache line will collide, and LL/SC operations in the same exclusive reservation granule will collide, so the amount of store physically required is greater.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Wait-free algorithms were rare until 2011, both in research and in practice.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] However, in 2011 Kogan and Petrank presented a wait-free queue building on the CAS primitive, generally available on common hardware.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Their construction expanded the lock-free queue of Michael and Scott, which is an efficient queue often used in practice.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] A follow-up paper by Kogan and Petrank provided a method for making wait-free algorithms fast and used this method to make the wait-free queue practically as fast as its lock-free counterpart.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] A subsequent paper by Timnat and Petrank provided an automatic mechanism for generating wait-free data structures from lock-free ones.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Thus, wait-free implementations are now available for many data-structures.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Under reasonable assumptions, Alistarh, Censor-Hillel, and Shavit showed that lock-free algorithms are practically wait-free.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Thus, in the absence of hard deadlines, wait-free algorithms may not be worth the additional complexity that they introduce.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Lock-freedom allows individual threads to starve but guarantees system-wide throughput.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] An algorithm is lock-free if, when the program threads are run for a sufficiently long time, at least one of the threads makes progress (for some sensible definition of progress).
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] In particular, if one thread is suspended, then a lock-free algorithm guarantees that the remaining threads can still make progress.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Hence, if two threads can contend for the same mutex lock or spinlock, then the algorithm is *not* lock-free.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] An algorithm is lock-free if infinitely often operation by some processors will succeed in a finite number of steps.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] For instance, if *N* processors are trying to execute an operation, some of the *N* processes will succeed in finishing the operation in a finite number of steps and others might fail and retry on failure.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] The difference between wait-free and lock-free is that wait-free operation by each process is guaranteed to succeed in a finite number of steps, regardless of the other processors.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] In general, a lock-free algorithm can run in four phases: completing one's own operation, assisting an obstructing operation, aborting an obstructing operation, and waiting.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Completing one's own operation is complicated by the possibility of concurrent assistance and abortion, but is invariably the fastest path to completion.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] The decision about when to assist, abort or wait when an obstruction is met is the responsibility of a *contention manager*.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] This may be very simple (assist higher priority operations, abort lower priority ones), or may be more optimized to achieve better throughput, or lower the latency of prioritized operations.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Correct concurrent assistance is typically the most complex part of a lock-free algorithm, and often very costly to execute: not only does the assisting thread slow down, but thanks to the mechanics of shared memory, the thread being assisted will be slowed, too, if it is still running.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Obstruction-freedom is the weakest natural non-blocking progress guarantee.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] An algorithm is obstruction-free if at any point, a single thread executed in isolation (i.e., with all obstructing threads suspended) for a bounded number of steps will complete its operation.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] All lock-free algorithms are obstruction-free.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Obstruction-freedom demands only that any partially completed operation can be aborted and the changes made rolled back.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Dropping concurrent assistance can often result in much simpler algorithms that are easier to validate.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Preventing the system from continually live-locking is the task of a contention manager.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Some obstruction-free algorithms use a pair of "consistency markers" in the data structure.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Processes reading the data structure first read one consistency marker, then read the relevant data into an internal buffer, then read the other marker, and then compare the markers.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] The data is consistent if the two markers are identical.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] Markers may be non-identical when the read is interrupted by another process updating the data structure.
[src:fasthttp-go/non-blocking-algorithm] In such a case, the process discards the data in the internal buffer and tries again.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] Under HTTP 1.0, connections should always be **closed** by the server after sending the response.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] Since at least late 1995, developers of popular products (browsers, web servers, etc.) using HTTP/1.0, started to add an unofficial extension (to the protocol) named "keep-alive" in order to allow the reuse of a connection for multiple requests/responses.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] When the server receives this request and generates a response, if it supports keep-alive then it also adds the same above header to the response.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] Following this, the connection is not dropped, but is instead kept open.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] When the client sends another request, it uses the same connection.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] After that the connection is closed following specified rules.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] Since 1997, the various versions of HTTP/1.1 specifications acknowledged the usage of this unofficial extension and included a few caveats regarding the interoperability between HTTP/1.0 (keep-alive) and HTTP/1.1 clients / servers.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] In HTTP 1.1, all connections are considered persistent unless declared otherwise.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] The HTTP **persistent connections** do not use separate keepalive messages, they just allow multiple requests to use a single connection.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] However, the default connection timeout of Apache httpd 1.3 and 2.0 is as little as 15 seconds and just 5 seconds for Apache httpd 2.2 and above.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] The advantage of a short timeout is the ability to deliver multiple components of a web page quickly while not consuming resources to run multiple server processes or threads for too long.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] Keepalive makes it difficult for the client to determine where one response ends and the next response begins, particularly during pipelined HTTP operation.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] This is a serious problem when `Content-Length` cannot be used due to streaming.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] To solve this problem, HTTP 1.1 introduced a chunked transfer coding that defines a `last-chunk` bit.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] The `last-chunk` bit is set at the end of each response so that the client knows where the next response begins.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] According to RFC 7230, section 6.4, "a client ought to limit the number of simultaneous open connections that it maintains to a given server".
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] The previous version of the HTTP/1.1 specification stated specific maximum values but in the words of RFC 7230 "this was found to be impractical for many applications... instead... be conservative when opening multiple connections".
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] These guidelines are intended to improve HTTP response times and avoid congestion.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] If HTTP pipelining is correctly implemented, there is no performance benefit to be gained from additional connections, while additional connections may cause issues with congestion.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] If the client does not close the connection when all of the data it needs has been received, the resources needed to keep the connection open on the server will be unavailable for other clients.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] This affects both server's availability and the availability of resources on the server, with the degree of impact depending on the server's architecture and configuration.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] Also a race condition can occur where the client sends a request to the server at the same time that the server closes the TCP connection.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] A server should send a 408 Request Timeout status code to the client immediately before closing the connection.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] When a client receives the 408 status code, after having sent the request, it may open a new connection to the server and re-send the request.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] Not all clients will re-send the request, and many that do will only do so if the request has an idempotent HTTP method.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] All modern web browsers including Chrome, Edge, Firefox, Opera (since 4.0), and Safari use persistent connections.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] In Firefox, the number of simultaneous connections can be customized (per-server, per-proxy, total).
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] Persistent connections time out after 115 seconds (1.92 minutes) of inactivity which is changeable via the configuration.
[src:fasthttp-go/persistent-connection] Python's `requests` library contains `requests.Session()`, which establishes a persistent HTTP connection, thereby allowing the underlying TCP connection to be reused, which can result in a significant performance increase.
[src:fasthttp-go/web-server-benchmarking] The measurements must be performed under a varying load of clients and requests per client.
[src:fasthttp-go/web-server-benchmarking] Web application benchmarks measure the performance of application servers and database servers used to host web applications.
[src:fasthttp-go/web-server-benchmarking] TPC-W was a common benchmark emulating an online bookstore with synthetic workload generation.
